docs/usage/Basic.html.body:
Basic Usage
Setup
If you did not use Fela yet, I highly recommend reading through the whole documentation.
You should read the Usage with React guide and wrap your whole application with the &lt;Provider&gt; component provided by react-fela.

After setting up react-fela, you can simply import any Kilvin component and use it as is.
Example
import React from &apos;react&apos;
import { render } from &apos;react-dom&apos;
import { RendererProvider } from &apos;react-fela&apos;
import { createRenderer } from &apos;fela&apos;
import plugins from &apos;fela-preset-web&apos;

import { Absolute, Box } from &apos;kilvin&apos;

const renderer = createRenderer({
  plugins,
})

render(
  &lt;RendererProvider renderer={renderer}&gt;
    &lt;Box space={2}&gt;
      &lt;Absolute top={0} left={0} fixed&gt;
        Fixed in the upper left corner.
      &lt;/Absolute&gt;
      &lt;Box padding={2}&gt;A&lt;/Box&gt;
      &lt;Box padding={3} width={50}&gt;
        B
      &lt;/Box&gt;
    &lt;/Box&gt;
  &lt;/RendererProvider&gt;,
  document.getElementById(&apos;app&apos;)
)

docs/usage/Advanced.html.body:
Advanced Usage
Despite the basic usage, we can also add some Fela plugins to make the components (especially &lt;Box&gt;) even more useful.
Responsive Values
A great way to extend the ability of our components is by adding the responsive-value plugin. That way we can pass arrays of values mapping to individual breakpoints.
In order to make it work we need to provide a function that resolves the media queries based on the array length and a list of supported properties.
Setup
import { createRenderer } from &apos;fela&apos;
import responsiveValue from &apos;fela-plugin-responsive-value&apos;

// if we have 2 values, use default and large media query
// if we get 3, also use a tablet media query in between
const getMediaQueries = (values, props) =&gt; {
  if (values.length === 2) {
    return [&apos;@media (min-width: 1024px)&apos;]
  }

  return [&apos;@media (min-width: 800px)&apos;, &apos;@media (min-width: 1024px)&apos;]
}

const renderer = createRenderer({
  plugins: [
    responsiveValue(getMediaQueries, {
      padding: true,
      paddingTop: true,
      paddingRight: true,
      paddingBottom: true,
      paddingLeft: true,
      margin: true,
      marginTop: true,
      marginRight: true,
      marginBottom: true,
      marginLeft: true,
    }),
  ],
})

Usage
import { Box } from &apos;kilvin&apos;

export default () =&gt; (
  &lt;Box padding={[4, 6, 8]}&gt;
    &lt;Box width={300}&gt;A&lt;/Box&gt;
  &lt;/Box&gt;
)

One can also skip breakpoints by passing an empty item e.g. [4, ,8]
Baseline Grid
Box and Spacer have some props that rely on a baseline grid that can be passed with a theme.
It is optional and defaults to 1 making sure to also work without a theme.
import { ThemeProvider } from &apos;react-fela&apos;
import { Box } from &apos;kilvin&apos;

const theme = {
  baselineGrid: 4,
}

export default () =&gt; (
  &lt;ThemeProvider theme={theme}&gt;
    &lt;Box padding={4}&gt;
      I have a 16px padding and this is a 16px spacer!
      &lt;Spacer size={4} /&gt;
    &lt;/Box&gt;
  &lt;/ThemeProvider&gt;
)

docs/components/ScrollView.html.body:
ScrollView
ScrollView is a simple component adding scrollbars for overflowing content.
It renders a &lt;Box&gt; component under the hood with some additional defaults.
It supports all props that are supported by &lt;Box&gt; as well.
Defaults
{
  -webkit-overflow-scrolling: touch;
  overflow: auto;
  flex-shrink: 1;
  flex-grow: 1;
  max-height: 100%;
}

Example
import { ScrollView } from &apos;kilvin&apos;

const List = () =&gt; (
  &lt;ScrollView height={50} extend={{ backgroundColor: &apos;red&apos; }}&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;Item 1&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;Item 2&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;Item 3&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;Item 4&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;Item 5&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;Item 6&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;Item 7&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;Item 8&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;Item 9&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;/ScrollView&gt;
)

docs/components/Spacer.html.body:
Spacer
Spacer simply adds whitespace.
It renders a &lt;Box&gt; passing both basis and widthto act as a spacer.
Props



Property
Value
Description




size
(number)
Whitespace size as a multiple of the baselineGrid.



Example
import { Spacer, Box } from &apos;kilvin&apos;

export default () =&gt; (
  &lt;Box&gt;
    &lt;Box&gt;We are separated&lt;/Box&gt;
    &lt;Spacer size={30} /&gt;
    &lt;Box&gt;by 30px&lt;/Box&gt;
  &lt;/Box&gt;
)
